ner’, a primary derivative of <i>drāen</i> ‘turn, spin’). A turner would make small objects not just from wood, but also from bone, ivory, and amber, all of which were widely used in the Middle Ages for their decorative value. This surname is also found in Poland and Czechia. See also   Drechsler  , compare   Tressler  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Trussel was born in 1384, in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Geoffrey Trussel II, was 22 and her mother, Mrs. Geoffrey Trussel II, was 21. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas Woodan. She died in Burbage, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1384–":"1384–Surnud","1384–Female":"1384–Surnud","1380–1431":"1380–1431","1405–1431":"1405–1431","1362–1412":"1362–1412","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1412":"1412","1431":"1431","1364":"1364","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burbage, Leicestershire, England":"Burbage, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burbage, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Burbage, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United